rlm-tsconv NUMBER

Convert a numeric input to a date/time, auto-detecting both the base
of the input and the magnitude (unit) of the timestamp. Useful when
you have a raw Unix epoch number from a log line, a database row, or
an HTTP header and want to see what date and time it represents
without having to remember which unit the producer chose.

Input parsing — the first form that matches wins:
  * 0x...  / 0o... / 0b...   — hex / octal / binary literals
  * bare hex                 — used when the digits contain any of a-f
  * decimal                  — the default
  * underscores `_` in the digits are stripped before parsing
    (so `1_700_000_000` is the same as `1700000000`)

Unit inference — chosen by the absolute magnitude of the integer:
  * abs(n) < 10**11   →  seconds
  * abs(n) < 10**14   →  milliseconds
  * abs(n) < 10**17   →  microseconds
  * else              →  nanoseconds

The boundaries cleanly separate plausible epoch values in s / ms /
µs / ns for any year from ~1973 onward. A negative integer is
treated as a pre-epoch timestamp.

Output (one field per line):
  input    — the original argument as you passed it
  decimal  — the parsed value in base 10
  hex      — the parsed value in hex
  inferred — which unit was picked
  local    — date/time in the local timezone
  utc      — date/time in UTC
  relative — humanized delta (e.g. `3h 12m ago`, `45d 6h from now`)

ARGUMENTS
  NUMBER   The number to convert. May also be supplied on stdin
           (e.g. `pbpaste | tsconv`).

REQUIRES
  python3
